{"ts":"2026-06-27T04:23:55.914Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Designing the Dashboard**\n\nI'm focusing on crafting a premium experience for the AI Operations page, specifically `/portal/ai-operations/page.tsx`. Currently, I'm at the layout stage, and working to define the metrics we'll be displaying. I have a couple of key ones in mind already. Specifically, I'm thinking about \"Total Active Agents\" and \"Average CPU Utilization\" as good initial pieces of data.\n\n\n**Expanding the Dashboard Metrics**\n\nI've expanded the planned metrics for the AI Operations page, incorporating \"Active Loops/Threads\" and \"Compliance Guardrails Status\". Also, I'm carefully reviewing the requirements and building out the structure of the `/portal/ai-operations` page. I am going to make it into the client-facing AI operations command center. Finally, I've got to ensure the UI has a premium look and feel.\n\n\n**Defining the Layout Structure**\n\nI'm now establishing the core framework for the AI Operations command center. I've broken down the design into interactive elements. We have interactive filter options. I am also working on: circular health rings using SVGs, and interactive tabs. There will be Tab 1: Agent Registry & Telemetry Cards. Tab 2: Governance & Compliance Policy. Tab 3: Enclave Runtime & Execution Timeline.\n\n\n**Adding the Oversight Link**\n\nI'm integrating an executive control panel into the AI Operations page, with a direct link to the Oversight Control Center. I am making it feel like a command center for the entire system! I'm also planning subtle motion transitions and am working on responsive layout. I will maintain a clean design using a premium color scheme and spacious layout, avoiding visual clutter. I've now checked to see if the routes are in place, and found the page listing! I am now ready to add the link in the header.\n\n\n**Implementing the Oversight Link**\n\nI've successfully integrated the \"Go to Control Center ->\" link, ensuring seamless navigation to `/portal/control-center`, addressing the oversight control requirement. I also checked the mock data models in `lib/mock-data-model.ts` and realized I can extend them for a high-fidelity page, while maintaining core type safety. Now, I'm designing the SVG health rings: I'm planning to make them circular progress bars with glowing gradients and drop shadows, to show CPU, memory, network/uptime, and thread load. Finally, I will implement dropdown filters for the project, agent type, status, and operating stage.\n\n\n**Adding Interactive Filters**\n\nI'm now implementing functional dropdown filters for project, agent type, and status, along with a search input. The goal is real-time list updates in response to user input. I'm focusing on ensuring these elements are highly interactive, and making sure the UI responds promptly to every change. I am confident in creating a full, high-fidelity implementation of the `/app/portal/ai-operations/page.tsx` soon, now that these interactive elements are in place. I have to design the mock data and types we need, and decided to do that right within the page. I'm also planning the layout and tabs.\n\nI am working on the page structure, and the Header Section will include Title: `AI Operations & Telemetry Command Enclave` and a description.\n\n\n**Designing the System View**\n\nI'm now integrating a comprehensive Executive Overview Section to provide a clear picture of managed AI operations. I'm focusing on \"SYSTEM STATUS: SECURE\" with a pulsating light, and crafting four metric cards. These cards will feature SVG circular health rings, providing visual representations of Core Load, Isolated RAM, Uptime SLA, and Thread Pools. The goal is to provide a real-time, at-a-glance view of the system. I'm also ensuring the filters from before are present.\n\n\n\n**Defining the Tabbed System**\n\nI'm now designing the tabbed content system for the AI Operations page. I will focus on a pivot tabs structure with three key tabs: Active Agents Telemetry, Governance & Compliance Guardrails, and Hardware Runtime & Execution Timeline. Within \"Active Agents Telemetry\", I'm planning a detailed display of agent telemetry data, including name, status badges, CPU/Memory gauges, and a live simulation log. Action buttons like \"Recycle Core Enclave\" and \"Telemetry Detail\" will provide interactive control and navigation. I'll include elegant empty states for filter scenarios. Finally, Tab 2 will focus on guardrails.\n\n\n**Visualizing the Timeline**\n\nI'm now designing Tab 3, \"Hardware Runtime & Execution Timeline.\" I'm creating a narrative SVG timeline to map agent lifecycles, with each phase clearly marked. I'm focusing on \"Enclave Provisioning,\" \"Context Cache Loading,\" \"Alignment Guardrail Injection,\" \"Autonomous Loop Execution,\" and \"Decoupled State Archiving.\" Also, I'm going to include hardware specs like hypervisor details, CPU pinning, and memory keys, all styled elegantly. I'll make use of our Lucide React icons and Tailwind CSS.\n\n\n**Importing the Icons**\n\nI've decided on a set of Lucide icons to use: Bot, Activity, Cpu, ShieldCheck, HelpCircle, Layers, ArrowRight, RefreshCw, Search, ChevronDown, ListFilter, Terminal, Compass, AlertTriangle, CheckCircle, Clock. I'm focusing on ensuring all the icons look gorgeous. Now I'm preparing to craft the page's code, focusing on clean spacing, color palettes, and those SVG rings! I'll double-check all file paths and imports.\n\\n\\n\nI'm now verifying the accessibility of the mock data model and its exports, particularly `previewAgentOperations` in `@/lib/mock-data-model`. I'm examining the fields of `AgentOperation`, which includes `id`, `name`, `projectId`, `status`, and `threads`. I will make sure they are used and displayed in the AI operations page.\n\n\n**Extending the Data Model**\n\nI'm now integrating properties for memory, logs, and lastHeartbeat into the agent data model. This will let us to beautifully map richer objects locally, and visualize them within the system. I'm focusing on defining how the SVG health ring will look.\n\n\n**Visualizing the Health Rings**\n\nI'm now implementing the SVG health rings, which will render perfectly within the executive summary. They look great and provide concise visual data. I've designed the markup for these: circular progress bars with glowing gradients and drop shadows.\n\n\n**Implementing the Filters**\n\nI'm now integrating new agent filter options for project ID, agent type, status, and operating stage. The data includes projects like \"proj-001\" and \"proj-002\", agent prefixes such as \"RETAIL\" and \"ALIGN,\" and statuses like \"active\" and \"evaluating.\" I've also set up a tabbed system for easy navigation.\n\n\n**Verifying the Policies**\n\nI'm now verifying our system policies to reflect a high security state. I'm checking that the NIST AI Risk Management Framework (v1.0) and AMD SEV Hardware Cryptographic Seal verification are both valid. The State Synchronization Guardrail is valid. I'm also confirming the eBPF Telemetry Outbound Network Filter is active.\n\n\n**Reviewing the Page Layout**\n\nI'm now reviewing the code structure for `/app/portal/ai-operations/page.tsx`, and ensuring proper component imports. I'm importing standard components like `useState` and `useMemo`, alongside icons from `lucide-react`, and also `previewAgentOperations` from the mock data model. I will verify if `previewAgentOperations` is already imported/exported in `components/private-app`. Then I will start crafting the page!\n\n\n**Validating the Import Path**\n\nI've verified the import path for the mock data model. The import from `@/lib/mock-data-model` is fully valid. I checked, and that path will work properly. Then I will start crafting the page!\n\n\n"}}
