{"ts":"2026-06-27T04:24:18.633Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Verifying Feature Requirements**\n\nI've decided that `PrivatePageHeader` is indeed a great standard, and a beautiful one at that. Now, I'm setting my sights on replacing `app/portal/ai-operations/page.tsx` with a premium, custom layout that's highly interactive and designed by a senior designer. My next step involves carefully verifying and cataloging the required features and items for this endeavor. The target is `/portal/ai-operations`.\n\n\n**Defining Operating Stage Attributes**\n\nI'm now zeroing in on defining the \"Operating Stage\" attribute for the agent operation mock items. I'm imagining a comprehensive dashboard UI with status rails, agent cards, health rings, and a timeline. The system needs filters for Project, Agent Type, Status, and of course, Operating Stage. Remember, it's all frontend; no backend! And preview data is clearly marked. Now, I will do a lint and build.\n\n\n**Implementing Filter Reactivity**\n\nI'm focusing now on implementing reactive filters. I'll utilize React state for each dropdown, namely `search`, `selectedProject`, `selectedType`, `selectedStatus`, and `selectedStage`. The goal is complete reactivity! I need to ensure the system filters data according to the selected values. I've also defined example attributes for the agent operation mock items, which include Project, Status, Agent Type, and importantly, Stage.\n\n\n**Filtering Agent Operations**\n\nI'm now implementing the filtering logic for the agent operations list using `useMemo`. I'm starting by defining the conditions for search, project, agent type, status, and operating stage filters. I'm focusing on ensuring each filter reacts correctly to the user's selections, ensuring they can be filtered accurately based on user choices.\n\n\n**Visualizing Core UI Elements**\n\nI'm now determining the visual components for the three tabs. In Tab 1, I'm thinking of a display for filtered agent cards. Each card will contain a custom status badge, an active threads meter, and a context cache indicator. There will be a real-time simulation log console, and an interaction button labeled \"Recycle Enclave.\" I'll also add a link button for detailed analysis.\n\n\n**Implementing Local UI State**\n\nI'm now implementing local React state to make the page more interactive, focusing on the \"Recycle Enclave\" button's functionality. When clicked, I'll update the local state for `agentsState` which holds agent operations. This will dynamically reflect status changes and simulation logs in the UI, enhancing user interaction. It also involves the use of `useMemo` for filtering.\n\n\n**Categorizing Agent Types**\n\nI've just added logic to categorize agent types based on their names using `startsWith`. I'm using \"RETAIL\", \"ALIGN\", \"ORE\", \"MED\", and \"TRANS\" for this. I've also implemented conditional checks for `matchesType`, `matchesStatus`, and `matchesStage` based on the selected filters. My focus is on the `operatingStage`, where I've defined stages based on the agent's status (\"active\", \"evaluating\", \"warning\", \"decoupled\") to ensure matching stage filters.\n\n\n**Simulating Hardware Reboot**\n\nI'm now implementing the \"Recycle Core Enclave\" action. When clicked, I'll set `rebooting` to `true` for that agent. After 1.5 seconds, I'll update it to `false`, append success logs, and, optionally, transition the agent's status. This interaction is key for a premium UI feel! I'm creating the recycle function and will add the log updates.\n\n\n**Designing Policy Visualizations**\n\nI'm now determining how to display active policies in Tab 2, specifically for governance and compliance. I'm focusing on crafting an elegant list or table, using the provided policy data as a foundation. I'm imagining using the data I have to create an interactive display. I'm eager to explore policy details.\n\n\n**Visualizing Policy Compliance**\n\nI'm now figuring out how to showcase policy compliance data in Tab 2 in an engaging way. I'm focusing on crafting a compelling UI to display these active policies elegantly. I am impressed by the high-quality details, so this should be a great design opportunity. The goal is to provide a clean display that presents and highlights each policy's status and relevant details, making complex information digestible.\n\n\n**Visualizing Hardware Timeline**\n\nI'm now designing Tab 3 to showcase hardware runtime specs and an execution timeline. I've compiled specs, including Hypervisor, CPU Isolation, HSM Seals, and Encryption Engine details. Now, I'm working on a vertical timeline visualization for cryptographic events, with details like sandbox provisioning, HSM validation, model weight decryption, and telemetry stream establishment. I'm focusing on creating an elegant and informative UI element.\n\n\n"}}
